  "prompt": "Can you use a rented apartment as office space for a startup in London? What are the potential challenges? Do you know people successfully doing it?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive breakdown:\n\nLegal/Contractual Considerations:\n- Check lease agreement for restrictions on business use\n- Some residential leases prohibit commercial activities\n- May need landlord's explicit permission\n- Some areas have planning restrictions\n\nPotential Challenges:\n1. Noise and disruption\n2. Increased wear and tear\n3. Potential insurance complications\n4. Higher utility costs\n5. Potential conflict with neighbors\n6. Limited space for meetings/equipment\n\nPractical Solutions:\n- Use part of apartment, not whole space\n- Maintain professional boundaries\n- Consider co-working spaces as alternative\n- Ensure good sound insulation\n- Be transparent with landlord\n\nReal-World Examples:\n- Many tech startups in London begin in apartments\n- Particularly common in areas like Shoreditch\n- Companies like TransferWise (Wise) started similarly\n- Successful founders often begin in home/shared spaces\n\nRecommended Steps:\n1. Review lease carefully\n2. Communicate with landlord\n3. Check local planning regulations\n4. Consider hybrid working model\n5. Plan for potential scaling\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of working from a rented apartment?",
